Stereotype threat is a term used to describe the negative impact that social stereotypes, once activated, can have on task performance.   Can stereotype threat negatively impact performance even of people who otherwise are high performers?

o answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Texas at Austin and Stanford University conducted an experiment. A group of white students who identified strongly with high math ability and had high SAT math scores (610 or above) participated in this study. Half the participants were assigned to the stereotype condition and reminded about how Asians are superior to other groups in mathematics. The other half of participants was assigned to the control group and were not told about this, instead reading a generic story about how mathematics is important. All participants completed an exam similar to SAT math, consisting of 15 calculus-based questions. The measure of interest was how many of the questions were solved successfully.

Can stereotype threat be reduced by describing a task as not producing differences between different social groups?

To answer this question, a group of psychologists from the University of Waterloo, Stanford University, and the University of Michigan conducted an experiment. In this experiment, participants with no advanced math training completed two versions of an advanced GRE math test, one after the other. Participants were told that the first test was one on which there were gender differences and that the second test was one on which there were no gender differences (order counterbalanced across participants). In reality the tests were similar. Half the participants were men and the other half women. The measure of interest is the number of items correctly solved in the tests.

Stereotype threat is a term used to describe the negative impact that social stereotypes, once activated, can have on task performance.   For stereotype threat to take place, is it important that people identify with the ability targeted by the stereotype?

login_session: To answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Texas at Austin and Stanford University conducted an experiment. In this study participants who had previously completed a questionnaire regarding their attitudes towards math (i.e., how important math performance was for them), were divided into two groups based on their scores in that questionnaire: high math-identified vs. moderately identified. In addition, half of the participants in each group were assigned to a stereotype threat manipulation condition, whereas the other half were assigned to the control group. All participants were white male students from the University of Texas at Austin. In the the stereotype threat condition participants were reminded how Asians are superior to other groups in mathematics. Participants in the control group were not told about this, instead reading a generic story about how mathematics is important. All participants completed an exam similar to SAT math, consisting of 15 calculus-based questions. The measure of interest was how many of the questions were solved successfully.

The researchers hypothesised that, if identification with the ability does not play a role in the negative effect of the stereotype introduced, then we should see no difference between students with high and moderate math identification.

The graph on the right shows the results of this study. As you can see, participants who cared deeply about their math abilities (high math identified), performed better in the control condition than in the stereotype-threat condition. However, for participants who did not care as deeply about their math abilities (moderate math identified), this pattern was reversed.

The researchers concluded that the results of this study indicate that domain-identification -- feeling that the domain is important to you -- plays a role on whether activating stereotypes has a detrimental effect on performance or not. This is because, if we do not identify with the domain of the stereotype, we are unlikely to activate stereotype implications regarding our ability in the task.

supplement: Stereotype threat is a term used to describe the negative impact that social stereotypes, once activated, can have on task performance.   Can stereotype threat be reduced by describing a task as not producing differences between different social groups?

login_session: To answer this question, a group of psychologists from the University of Waterloo, Stanford University, and the University of Michigan conducted an experiment. In this experiment, participants with no advanced math training completed two versions of an advanced GRE math test, one after the other. Participants were told that the first test was one on which there were gender differences and that the second test was one on which there were no gender differences (order counterbalanced across participants). In reality the tests were similar. Half the participants were men and the other half women. The measure of interest is the number of items correctly solved in the tests.

The researchers predicted that being told that the test elicited gender differences would activate math performance stereotypes (namely that women perform poorly) and depress women performance in the test. However, when this stereotype was not activated, no differences in performance would be seen between the two groups.

The graph on the right shows the results from this experiment. As you can see, when the participants were told that the test elicited no gender differences, men and women performed equally well on the test. However, when told that the test elicited gender differences men performed better than women on the test.

The researchers concluded that by presenting the test as one on which gender differences do not occur, they made the stereotype of women’s math inability irrelevant to interpreting their performance on the test—this particular test. It allowed these women to be as unconcerned with the gender-based stereotype as equally qualified men, which, in turn, allowed them to perform as well as these men. These findings provide strong evidence that women’s underperformance on these difficult math tests results from stereotype threat, rather than from sex-linked ability differences that are detectable only on advanced math material.

supplement: Stereotype threat is a term used to describe the negative impact that social stereotypes, once activated, can have on task performance.   Can stereotype threat negatively impact performance even of people who otherwise are high performers?

login_session: To answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Texas at Austin and Stanford University conducted an experiment. A group of white students who identified strongly with high math ability and had high SAT math scores (610 or above) participated in this study. Half the participants were assigned to the stereotype condition and reminded about how Asians are superior to other groups in mathematics. The other half of participants was assigned to the control group and were not told about this, instead reading a generic story about how mathematics is important. All participants completed an exam similar to SAT math, consisting of 15 calculus-based questions. The measure of interest was how many of the questions were solved successfully.

The researchers hypothesised that, not only people who might perform poorly on a particular task were affected by stereotype activation, but even people who often perform well would also have their scores negatively impacted by the activation of a stereotype that emphasizes possible failure.
The graph on the right shows the results of this study. As you can see, participants performed better in the control condition than in the stereotype-threat condition.

The researchers concluded that the results of this study indicate that high ability participants were also affected by the activation of a negative stereotype. This indicates that stereotype threat does not involve only the activation of pre-existing doubts about our performance in the task.

Misattribution of arousal describes the process whereby people make a mistake in assuming what is causing them to feel aroused.

For example, when actually experiencing physiological responses related to fear, people mislabel those responses as romantic arousal. Does the valence of the arousal affect the direction of the misattribution effect?

To answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Maryland, University of Notre Dame, and Rutgers University conducted an experiment. In this study, the researchers tested whether arousal with both positive and negative valence increased attra

In this study, the researchers tested whether arousal with both positive and negative valence increased attractiveness ratings of an actor compared to a low arousal condition. Male participants were divided into one of 3 groups. Participants in one of the groups started by listening to a tapped testimony of a grisly murder (Negative Arousal Condition). Participants in another group started by listening to a taped recording of a comedy show (Positive Arousal Condition). The last group listened to a description of the frog’s circulatory system (Neutral Arousal Condition). Following this, all participants watched a video of a female actor in which the actor wore form-fitting attractive clothes, had her face and hair made up attractively, and delivered the script in an energetic way. After watching the video all participants filled a questionnaire rating the actor’s attractiveness. The measure of interest is the attractiveness rating in this questionnaire.
The researchers predicted that increased arousal (regardless of its valence) elicited by the audio recordings would increase attractiveness ratings compared to the neutral arousal condition.

supplement: To answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Maryland, University of Notre Dame, and Rutgers University conducted an experiment. In this study, the researchers tested whether arousal with both positive and negative valence increased attractiveness ratings of an actor compared to a low arousal condition. Male participants were divided into one of 3 groups. Participants in one of the groups started by listening to a tapped testimony of a grisly murder (Negative Arousal Condition). Participants in another group started by listening to a taped recording of a comedy show (Positive Arousal Condition). The last group listened to a description of the frog’s circulatory system (Neutral Arousal Condition). Following this, all participants watched a video of a female actor in which the actor wore form-fitting attractive clothes, had her face and hair made up attractively, and delivered the script in an energetic way. After watching the video all participants filled a questionnaire rating the actor’s attractiveness. The measure of interest is the attractiveness rating in this questionnaire.

To test this hypothesis, a group of psychologists at Arizona State University conducted a study. In this study the researchers manipulated the arousal level of the participant using exercise activity, as well as the salience of this activity. Participants (all men) were randomly assigned to one of the four conditions (high arousal & high salience, high arousal & low salience, low arousal & high salience, and low arousal & low salience). Participants were told that they were participating in a study gauging the relationship between attitude similarity and liking.

To test this hypothesis, a group of psychologists at Arizona State University conducted a study. In this study the researchers manipulated the arousal level of the participant using exercise activity, as well as the salience of this activity. Participants (all men) were randomly assigned to one of the four conditions (high arousal & high salience, high arousal & low salience, low arousal & high salience, and low arousal & low salience). Participants were told that they were participating in a study gauging the relationship between attitude similarity and liking.

They were informed that their attitudes would be measured and then correlated with those of a "female student also participating in the study," whom they would later meet for a short "date." The ostensible purpose was to determine whether there was a relationship between attitude similarities and dating preferences. The first part of the study consisted of measuring participants' attitudes on a variety of different topics. As the final part of the attitude-measurement phase, participants ran in place for either 15 s (low arousal) or for 2 min (high arousal), ostensibly to measure their attitudes toward exercise. After completing the exercise, participants rated the activity on a variety of dimensions just as they had the previous stimuli. The exercise was treated as just another part of the measurement of participants' attitudes. Participants were then shown a videotape of the female "participant" they were expecting to meet. In the high-salience condition, participants viewed the videotape in the same room in which they had done the exercise, were specifically asked about the exercise activity ("How arousing was the exercise you just did?" and "OK, I want to be sure and get the order of this right, you just did the exercise, right? OK, the next thing is.. . .") and handed a questionnaire that also included questions about the exercise and how arousing it had been. In the low-salience condition, participants were not reminded of the exercise at any point and were led to another experimental room to view the tape. After watching the video of an attractive female participant, participants completed a questionnaire regarding romantic attraction towards the woman. The measure of interest is the attractiveness rating in this questionnaire.

The researchers predicted that even in the presence of ostensive cues indicating that the arousal had been caused by the physical activity and not romantic attraction, participants would still rate the woman as more attractive in the high arousal condition because this misattribution is caused by response facilitation triggered by the physical activity.

supplement: To test this hypothesis, a group of psychologists at Arizona State University conducted a study. In this study the researchers manipulated the arousal level of the participant using exercise activity, as well as the salience of this activity. Participants (all men) were randomly assigned to one of the four conditions (high arousal & high salience, high arousal & low salience, low arousal & high salience, and low arousal & low salience). Participants were told that they were participating in a study gauging the relationship between attitude similarity and liking. They were informed that their attitudes would be measured and then correlated with those of a "female student also participating in the study," whom they would later meet for a short "date." The ostensible purpose was to determine whether there was a relationship between attitude similarities and dating preferences. The first part of the study consisted of measuring participants' attitudes on a variety of different topics. As the final part of the attitude-measurement phase, participants ran in place for either 15 s (low arousal) or for 2 min (high arousal), ostensibly to measure their attitudes toward exercise. After completing the exercise, participants rated the activity on a variety of dimensions just as they had the previous stimuli. The exercise was treated as just another part of the measurement of participants' attitudes. Participants were then shown a videotape of the female "participant" they were expecting to meet. In the high-salience condition, participants viewed the videotape in the same room in which they had done the exercise, were specifically asked about the exercise activity ("How arousing was the exercise you just did?" and "OK, I want to be sure and get the order of this right, you just did the exercise, right? OK, the next thing is.. . .") and handed a questionnaire that also included questions about the exercise and how arousing it had been. In the low-salience condition, participants were not reminded of the exercise at any point and were led to another experimental room to view the tape. After watching the video of an attractive female participant, participants completed a questionnaire regarding romantic attraction towards the woman. The measure of interest is the attractiveness rating in this questionnaire.

supplement: Can misattribution of arousal change how confident we feel before completing a task?
Can misattribution of arousal change how confident we feel before completing a task?

To answer this question a group of psychologists at Williams College, Northwestern University and Cornell University conducted an experiment. Participants were randomly assigned to one of two groups: misattribution or control. All participants were told that they were participating in a study about the effects of subliminal noise on cognitive performance, specifically the ability to predict one’s performance in an upcoming task. Participants in both conditions were then asked to put the headphones on so that their subliminal tone threshold could be determined. In reality all participants were exposed to the same series of computer-generated sounds that decreased in volume, culminating in a silent “tone”. Participants were told that this final subliminal “tone” would be played while they make their predictions about completing an upcoming task, but not during the task itself. Participants in the misattribution condition were also told that this subliminal tone level has been found to cause individuals’ heart rates to increase and that people exposed to subliminal noise report feeling somewhat anxious or nervous. Participants in the control condition were told that the noise would not affect them in any way. After this, while being told that the “tone” was being played, participants made predictions about how well they would perform in upcoming tasks by reading the description of the task and rating their expected performance. Ratings of confidence in performing the upcoming task were the measure of interest.

he researchers predicted that confidence would be low in the control condition, but higher in the misattribution condition. This is because the arousal associated with task performance was likely to be misattributed to the tone presented.

isattribution of arousal describes the process whereby people make a mistake in assuming what is causing them to feel aroused. For example, when actually experiencing physiological responses related to fear, people mislabel those responses as romantic arousal. supplement: To answer this question a group of psychologists at Williams College, Northwestern University and Cornell University conducted an experiment. Participants were randomly assigned to one of two groups: misattribution or control. All participants were told that they were participating in a study about the effects of subliminal noise on cognitive performance, specifically the ability to predict one’s performance in an upcoming task. Participants in both conditions were then asked to put the headphones on so that their subliminal tone threshold could be determined. In reality all participants were exposed to the same series of computer-generated sounds that decreased in volume, culminating in a silent “tone”. Participants were told that this final subliminal “tone” would be played while they make their predictions about completing an upcoming task, but not during the task itself. Participants in the misattribution condition were also told that this subliminal tone level has been found to cause individuals’ heart rates to increase and that people exposed to subliminal noise report feeling somewhat anxious or nervous. Participants in the control condition were told that the noise would not affect them in any way. After this, while being told that the “tone” was being played, participants made predictions about how well they would perform in upcoming tasks by reading the description of the task and rating their expected performance. Ratings of confidence in performing the upcoming task were the measure of interest.

To answer this question a group of psychologists at Williams College, Northwestern University and Cornell University conducted an experiment. Participants were randomly assigned to one of two groups: misattribution or control. All participants were told that they were participating in a study about the effects of subliminal noise on cognitive performance, specifically the ability to predict one’s performance in an upcoming task. Participants in both conditions were then asked to put the headphones on so that their subliminal tone threshold could be determined. In reality all participants were exposed to the same series of computer-generated sounds that decreased in volume, culminating in a silent “tone”. Participants were told that this final subliminal “tone” would be played while they make their predictions about completing an upcoming task, but not during the task itself. Participants in the misattribution condition were also told that this subliminal tone level has been found to cause individuals’ heart rates to increase and that people exposed to subliminal noise report feeling somewhat anxious or nervous. Participants in the control condition were told that the noise would not affect them in any way. After this, while being told that the “tone” was being played, participants made predictions about how well they would perform in upcoming tasks by reading the description of the task and rating their expected performance. Ratings of confidence in performing the upcoming task were the measure of interest.

Misattribution of arousal describes the process whereby people make a mistake in assuming what is causing them to feel aroused. For example, when actually experiencing physiological responses related to fear, people mislabel those responses as romantic arousal. Can misattribution of arousal change how confident we feel before completing a task?

To answer this question a group of psychologists at Williams College, Northwestern University and Cornell University conducted an experiment. Participants were randomly assigned to one of two groups: misattribution or control. All participants were told that they were participating in a study about the effects of subliminal noise on cognitive performance, specifically the ability to predict one’s performance in an upcoming task. Participants in both conditions were then asked to put the headphones on so that their subliminal tone threshold could be determined. In reality all participants were exposed to the same series of computer-generated sounds that decreased in volume, culminating in a silent “tone”. Participants were told that this final subliminal “tone” would be played while they make their predictions about completing an upcoming task, but not during the task itself. Participants in the misattribution condition were also told that this subliminal tone level has been found to cause individuals’ heart rates to increase and that people exposed to subliminal noise report feeling somewhat anxious or nervous. Participants in the control condition were told that the noise would not affect them in any way. After this, while being told that the “tone” was being played, participants made predictions about how well they would perform in upcoming tasks by reading the description of the task and rating their expected performance. Ratings of confidence in performing the upcoming task were the measure of interest.
